item.title: Customizable Socket Tray + Divider & Height Offset
item.description:
I've long been looking for and printing socket holders/trays for my various automotive socket sets. I found the original Customizable Socket Tray and really liked it, but I wanted a few new features to fit my needs. So I decided to add those features and post this remix. Those features are:

Divider
Lets you easily put shallow and deep sockets together in one tray.

Height Offset
Lets you reduce the overall model height and save print material for extra large sockets (such as for axle nuts) that do not need as much side to side enclosure.

Look through the photos to see these features in action, as well as an actual model I made for some impact sockets, which I will post a full design for separately as a remix of this one in the future.

Thanks to the original designer Russell Stout (driftfox), who did all the hard work creating the original code, which is far more advanced than my simple additions. But I wanted to share my version for anyone who might also find it useful.

item.title: Garmin VivoActive 3/4 Venu Watch Strap Retainer
item.description:
Watch strap retainer band for the Garmin VivoActive 3/4 (also tested on the Garmin Venu strap). Should work with most 18/19mm silicon straps.

Two files are available:

  • Garmin VivoActive Watch Strap Retainer PLA.stl
  • Garmin VivoActive Watch Strap Retainer TPU.stl

The first has a shallower nub to catch the watch holes. If you're printing with a rigid filament (eg. PLA, ABS, etc.) then this leaves enough space to move the retainer and still catch the holes. If you're printing with a flexible filament (TPU), then the second file has a longer retainer and provides a better catch on the strap holes but you need to flex it a bit to release (like the stock retainer).

Designed with a flat edge to be printed without supports. Even when printed with rigid filament, the sharp edge remains comfortable for me.

item.title: Spice Corner Rack
item.description:
This is a spice rack that I have assembled from the size of my jars and the place where I needed it, I have used a 3mm wide DMF board. For the bottom part the board can be 48mm maximum and for the wall part 42mm maximum. You can use smaller boards or different materials if you wish. The length of the shelves is up to you, that's why there are the middle pieces to keep the rigidity of the shelf.

There is only one corner, making a mirror on the slicer will not be too complicated for you.

The plank at the bottom I have made a cut out with a socket so that it can be supported by a piece of wood, I hope you understand.

To anchor it you can use double sided tape or screws.

item.title: Suplemento para Rollos de 250g de Print_a_Lot
item.description:
Pieza para solucionar un pequeños defecto que tiene una partida de rollos de este gran fabricante argentino (https://www.printalot.es) recien llegado a Europa. El problema afecta, principalmente a las impresoras Artillery y cualquier otra que emplee un sistema similar de sujección de rollos.

Estos aros sirven para solucionar el problema en la mínima cantidad de tiempo (unos 80 minutos aprox) y con la minima cantidad de filamento (unos 9 grms)

Debeís de imprimir dos copias de la misma pieza, una para cada lado del rollo.

Esta solución es para los rollos de 250grms.

En breve subiré los mismos adaptados a los rollos de 1 Kgm.
item.author: candea69

item.title: MSFS2020 Twin Otter Throttle Levers for Honeycomb Bravo
item.description:
RC Tommy presents the Honeycomb Bravo compatible upside-down (roof mounted) Twin Otter throttle levers!

With the newly released Aerosoft DHC-6 Twin Otter for Microsoft Flight Simulator 2020 I truly felt the need for upside-down throttle levers for my Honeycomb Bravo throttle quadrant. In the lack of a good third party product, I decided to make these levers myself.

After a while I thought to myself: Why not share them with the community? Surely I can't be the only one flying the Twin Otter right now? Well, here you go - free of charge!

Please note that I have not made the prop- or condition levers yet, so in order to fit the throttle levers while the Honeycomb Throttle module is mounted upside down (roof mounted), I had to reverse the order of the levers (meaning throttle to the right, props in the middle and condition levers on the left side). This will be solved once I get around to make the rest of the levers for the Twin Otter in the future.

item.title: BIQU BX (H2) Filament Runout Sensor
item.description:
Deutsch:
Hier ein Halter für einen einfachen Filamentsensor (gekauft bei Aliexpress für ein paar Cent).
Der Halter bestekt aus zwei Teilen, die zusammengeschoben werden. Das vor dem Einbau einige Male machen, damit es leichtgängig wird. Wenn man mit Cura sliced, sollte man den zweiten Teil des Halters mit dem Wert -0.3 bei "Horizontale Erweiterung der ersten Schicht" belegen, dann lässt es sich nachher besser zusammenschieben.
Zur Befestigung benötigt man noch folgende Schrauben:
2 x M3x15
2 x M3x7 mit Senkkopf
Der Filamentsensor wird einfach von Hinten an den Teil 2 des Halters angeschraubt. Das Kabel des Filamenthalters kann man dann beim BIQU BX auf ca. 20 cm kürzen, mit einem neuen JST-PH Steckerchen (2.0 mm 3-polig) versehen und dann auf die kleine Platine wie im Foto zu sehen aufstecken. Das Kabel kann man genauso wie das Kabel vom Bed-Level-Sensor ins Gehäuse führen.
Für den Sensor muss natürlich die Marlin-Firmware etwas angepasst und neu kompiliert werden. Wenn man diese Firmware hier nimmt:
https://github.com/looxonline/Marlin/tree/BIQUBX_ALMOST_STOCK
dann ist es relativ einfach, nur die Zeile
"define FILAMENT_MOTION_SENSOR" in der configuration.h muss auskommentiert werden.
Dann funktioniert der Sensor einwandfrei, wenn man ihn mit
M412 S1
gefolgt von M500
einschaltet.
Den Sensorstatus bekommt man dann auch mit M119 angezeigt.
Einiges an Zubehör für den BIQU BX sowie gutes Filament findet ihr auch in meinem Onlineshop unter
https://www.3d-arbeitsplatz.de/
Schaut doch einmal rein, vielen Dank!

English:
Here's a holder for a simple filament sensor (bought on Aliexpress for pennies).
The holder consists of two parts that are pushed together. Do this a few times before installing to make it smoother. If you slice with Cura, you should assign the value -0.3 to "Horizontal extension of the first layer" to the second part of the holder, then it can be pushed together better afterwards.
The following screws are required for attachment:
2 x M3x15
2 x M3x7 with countersunk head
The filament sensor is simply screwed onto part 2 of the holder from behind. The cable of the filament holder can then be shortened to approx. 20 cm on the BIQU BX, fitted with a new JST-PH connector (2.0 mm 3-pin) and then plugged onto the small circuit board as shown in the photo. The cable can be fed into the housing in the same way as the cable from the bed-level sensor.
Of course, the Marlin firmware has to be adjusted and recompiled for the sensor. If you take this firmware here:
https://github.com/looxonline/Marlin/tree/BIQUBX_ALMOST_STOCK
then it's relatively easy, just the line
"define FILAMENT_MOTION_SENSOR" in configuration.h must be commented out.
Then the sensor works perfectly when you use it with
M412 S1
followed by M500
turns on.
The sensor status is then also displayed with M119.
You can also find some accessories for the BIQU BX as well as good filament in my online shop
https://www.3d-arbeitsplatz.de/
Take a look, thank you!
